    approach: "- Place two pointers at the leftmost and rightmost bars; the area is `(right - left) * min(height[left], height[right])`.\n- Always advance the pointer sitting at the **shorter** bar inward, because the current bar is the bottleneck — any move from the taller side can only keep or shrink width while the height is still capped by the shorter bar, so it can never beat the current answer.\n- Moving the shorter bar inward is the only way to discover a potentially taller bar that might compensate for the reduced width.\n- This greedy scan guarantees we never miss the optimal pair while visiting each element at most once.",
    code: "#include <vector>\n#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int maxArea(vector<int>& height) {\n        int left = 0, right = static_cast<int>(height.size()) - 1;\n        int best = 0;\n\n        while (left < right) {\n            // Area is limited by the shorter of the two bars\n            int water = (right - left) * min(height[left], height[right]);\n            best = max(best, water);\n\n            // Advance the pointer at the shorter bar — keeping the taller one\n            // is the only chance to improve the height constraint\n            if (height[left] < height[right])\n                ++left;\n            else\n                --right;\n        }\n\n        return best;\n    }\n};\n",
    timeComplexity: "O(n)",
