    approach: "- Build a 2-D DP table where `dp[i][j]` holds the LCS length for the first `i` characters of `text1` and `j` characters of `text2`.\n- If the current characters match, `dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1` — extend the LCS by one.\n- Otherwise, `dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])` — take the best result from ignoring one character from either string.\n- The base case (empty prefix of either string) naturally fills the zero-padded border row and column.",
    code: "#include <string>\n#include <vector>\n#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int longestCommonSubsequence(string text1, string text2) {\n        int m = text1.size(), n = text2.size();\n\n        // dp[i][j] = LCS length for text1[0..i-1] and text2[0..j-1]\n        // Row 0 and column 0 are implicitly 0 (empty prefix base case).\n        vector<vector<int>> dp(m + 1, vector<int>(n + 1, 0));\n\n        for (int i = 1; i <= m; ++i) {\n            for (int j = 1; j <= n; ++j) {\n                if (text1[i - 1] == text2[j - 1]) {\n                    // Characters match: extend the diagonal result\n                    dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;\n                } else {\n                    // No match: carry forward the best from either direction\n                    dp[i][j] = max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]);\n                }\n            }\n        }\n\n        return dp[m][n];\n    }\n};\n",
