    approach: "- Sort events by start day, then simulate day by day from day 1 up to the maximum end day.\n- On each day, push all newly-started events' end days into a min-heap (earliest-ending on top).\n- Evict any events from the heap whose end day has already passed, since they can no longer be attended.\n- Greedily attend the event that expires soonest (pop the heap top): this maximizes future flexibility by preserving events with later deadlines.",
    code: "#include <vector>\n#include <queue>\n#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int maxEvents(vector<vector<int>>& events) {\n        // Sort by start day so we can sweep left-to-right\n        sort(events.begin(), events.end(),\n             [](const auto& a, const auto& b){ return a[0] < b[0]; });\n\n        // Min-heap keyed on end day: always attend the soonest-expiring event\n        priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> pq;\n\n        int n = events.size();\n        int idx = 0; // pointer into sorted events\n        int attended = 0;\n\n        // Find the last possible day we ever need to simulate\n        int maxDay = 0;\n        for (const auto& e : events) maxDay = max(maxDay, e[1]);\n\n        for (int day = 1; day <= maxDay; ++day) {\n            // Enqueue every event that starts today\n            while (idx < n && events[idx][0] == day) {\n                pq.push(events[idx][1]);\n                ++idx;\n            }\n\n            // Drop events that have already expired (end day < today)\n            while (!pq.empty() && pq.top() < day) {\n                pq.pop();\n            }\n\n            // Attend the event ending soonest — greedy choice\n            if (!pq.empty()) {\n                pq.pop();\n                ++attended;\n            }\n        }\n\n        return attended;\n    }\n};\n",
