    approach: "- Maintain a `write` pointer that tracks the next position where a non-zero element should land.\n- Scan through the array with a `read` pointer; whenever a non-zero value is found, swap it into the `write` position and advance `write`.\n- Because every non-zero element is swapped into the earliest available slot, their original relative order is maintained and all displaced zeros accumulate at the tail.\n- One pass suffices, making the algorithm O(n) time and O(1) space.",
    code: "#include <vector>\n#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    void moveZeroes(vector<int>& nums) {\n        int write = 0; // next slot for a non-zero element\n\n        for (int read = 0; read < (int)nums.size(); ++read) {\n            if (nums[read] != 0) {\n                // Swap instead of overwrite: zeros naturally migrate right\n                swap(nums[write], nums[read]);\n                ++write;\n            }\n        }\n    }\n};\n",
