    approach: "- Use **binary exponentiation (fast power)**: at each step, if the current exponent bit is set, multiply the running result by the current base, then square the base and halve the exponent.\n- This reduces O(n) multiplications to O(log n) by exploiting the identity x^n = (x^2)^(n/2).\n- Handle negative exponents by taking the reciprocal of x and working with |n|; cast n to `long` first to safely negate INT_MIN without overflow.",
    code: "#include <cmath>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    double myPow(double x, int n) {\n        long exp = n;                  // avoid overflow when negating INT_MIN\n        if (exp < 0) {\n            x = 1.0 / x;\n            exp = -exp;\n        }\n\n        double result = 1.0;\n        // Binary exponentiation: O(log n) multiplications\n        while (exp > 0) {\n            if (exp & 1)               // odd exponent: absorb one factor\n                result *= x;\n            x *= x;                    // square the base\n            exp >>= 1;                 // halve the exponent\n        }\n        return result;\n    }\n};\n",
