    summary: "Given a sorted, non-overlapping list of intervals and a new interval to insert, return the merged list where the new interval is placed correctly and any overlapping intervals are combined into one.",
    approach: "- **Three-phase linear scan**: First, collect all intervals that end strictly before the new interval starts (no overlap, come before).\n- **Merge overlapping**: Expand the new interval by taking the min start and max end of any existing interval that overlaps with it.\n- **Append remainder**: After merging, push the (possibly expanded) new interval, then append all remaining intervals that start after it ends.\n- This works because the input is already sorted, so each phase can be done with a single forward pass in O(n) total.",
    code: "#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    vector<vector<int>> insert(vector<vector<int>>& intervals, vector<int>& newInterval) {\n        vector<vector<int>> result;\n        int n = intervals.size();\n        int i = 0;\n\n        // Phase 1: add all intervals that end before newInterval begins (no overlap)\n        while (i < n && intervals[i][1] < newInterval[0]) {\n            result.push_back(intervals[i++]);\n        }\n\n        // Phase 2: merge all overlapping intervals into newInterval\n        while (i < n && intervals[i][0] <= newInterval[1]) {\n            newInterval[0] = min(newInterval[0], intervals[i][0]);\n            newInterval[1] = max(newInterval[1], intervals[i][1]);\n            ++i;\n        }\n        result.push_back(newInterval);\n\n        // Phase 3: add remaining intervals that start after newInterval ends\n        while (i < n) {\n            result.push_back(intervals[i++]);\n        }\n\n        return result;\n    }\n};",
